CHAPTER XVI
LE       S MYSTERIOUS MOVEMENTS


Le remained at Mondreer, only riding over to Greenbushes
every day to superintend the repairs and refurnishing
of his house.
He never met Odalite except at meal times, and then
their chairs were so placed that neither need look in the
face of the other. Odalite       s seat was near the head of
the table. Le       s near the foot, on the same side. They
merely greeted each other on entering the dining room,
and that was all. Mr. and Mrs. Force treated their
young relative with the most delicate consideration.
102
Col. Anglesea treated his defeated rival with offensive
condescension.
Le tried to ignore the colonel       s existence, and found
his greatest comfort in the company of his little cousins.
Their warm, sincere love and sympathy was as balm to
his bruised heart.
The children had successfully passed their home examination
by the father, and their holidays had already
commenced, though it was a full week before Christmas.
And thus they were able to give their sailor cousin a
great deal of their society.
The mother and father did not interfere. They were
glad enough of any comfort or solace they could afford
